<subSubSection id="C35CACEA7C02CA6FFF21FB26255DFED0" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BF9FF617C02CA6FFF21FB2622A3FA1E" blockId="21.[145,761,1169,1897]" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFF21FB26216FFB03" box="[145,265,1170,1191]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Medium-sized (adult SVL 
<quantity id="4CBE52847C02CA6FFDFEFB252297FB03" box="[590,753,1169,1191]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.94" metricValueMax="7.27" metricValueMin="4.61" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" unit="mm" value="59.4" valueMax="72.7" valueMin="46.1">46.1–72.7 mm</quantity>
) terrestrial to semi-arboreal skinks with moderate limbs (forelimbs 27.0–39.8% of SVL, hindlimbs 31.7–48.7% of SVL); small lobules present on anterior edge of ear opening; two pairs of chin shields in medial contact; modally three supralabials posterior to subocular supralabial; chin shields separated from infralabials by a row of genials; lower eyelid scaly; temporal region fragmented (&gt; 3 scales); nasal scale undivided; frontoparietals unfused; viviparous; litter size 1–4.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF9FF617C02CA6FFF19FA70255DFED0" blockId="21.[145,761,1169,1897]" lastBlockId="21.[809,1425,197,372]" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFF19FA702131FA7D" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" box="[169,343,1476,1497]" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Alpinoscincus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFF19FA702131FA7D" box="[169,343,1476,1497]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Alpinoscincus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from all other genera by modally having three (vs. two) supralabials posterior to the subocular supralabial. It further differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFF21F9942159F991" authorityName="GREER" authorityYear="1974" box="[145,319,1568,1589]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Prasinohaema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFF21F9942159F991" box="[145,319,1568,1589]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Prasinohaema</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by lacking green blood and tissues, a prehensile tail with a glandular tip, and basally expanded subdigital lamellae. It further differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFF21F9C8208DF935" authorityName="Greer" authorityYear="1974" box="[145,235,1660,1681]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Lobulia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFF21F9C8208DF935" box="[145,235,1660,1681]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Lobulia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFF46F9C82124F935" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" box="[246,322,1660,1681]" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Palaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFF46F9C82124F935" box="[246,322,1660,1681]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Palaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFEC7F9C92273F936" authorityName="Allison &amp; Greer" authorityYear="1986" box="[375,533,1661,1682]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Papuascincus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFEC7F9C92273F936" box="[375,533,1661,1682]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Papuascincus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the lower eyelid scaly (vs. lower eyelid with a semi-transparent window), a fragmented (vs. the standard three-scale) temporal region and the chin shields separated from the infralabials by a row of genials (vs. chin shields abutting infralabials). It further differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFD1CF8A1229FF88E" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" box="[684,761,1813,1834]" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Palaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFD1CF8A1229FF88E" box="[684,761,1813,1834]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Palaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFF73F8812107F8EE" authorityName="Allison &amp; Greer" authorityYear="1986" box="[195,353,1845,1866]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Papuascincus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFF73F8812107F8EE" box="[195,353,1845,1866]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Papuascincus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having two pairs of chin shields in medial contact (vs. one pair), unfused (vs. fused) frontoparietals and a viviparous (vs. oviparous) reproductive mode. It further differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFA91FF502508FF5D" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" box="[1313,1390,228,249]" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Palaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFA91FF502508FF5D" box="[1313,1390,228,249]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Palaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its longer adult SVL (46.1–72.7 vs. 
<quantity id="4CBE52847C02CA6FFB6DFEB625EEFEBC" box="[1245,1416,258,280]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.925" metricValueMax="4.12" metricValueMin="3.7299999999999995" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" unit="mm" value="39.25" valueMax="41.2" valueMin="37.3">37.3–41.2 mm</quantity>
) and by lacking basally slightly expanded subidigital lamellae. It further differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFB73FEF4250CFEF1" authorityName="Allison &amp; Greer" authorityYear="1986" box="[1219,1386,320,341]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Papuascincus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFB73FEF4250CFEF1" box="[1219,1386,320,341]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Papuascincus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having an undivided (vs. divided) nasal scale.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35CACEA7C02CA6FFC99FE2924EFFD0D" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF9FF617C02CA6FFC99FE2923D2FD89" blockId="21.[809,1425,413,557]" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFC99FE2923CAFE16" box="[809,940,413,434]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Etymology:</emphasis>
A combinatorial noun derived from the Latin adjective 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFC6DFE082455FE75" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[989,1075,444,465]" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Alpinoscincus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alpinus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFC6DFE082455FE75" box="[989,1075,444,465]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">alpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, of high mountains, and Latin noun 
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFCC0FE6F23AEFE54" box="[880,968,475,496]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">scincus</emphasis>
, a 
<typeStatus id="54FD41C37C02CA6FFC42FE6F2440FE54" box="[1010,1062,475,496]" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">type</typeStatus>
of lizard, in reference to the extremely high elevations in which species in this genus occur.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF9FF617C02CA6FFC99FDE324EFFD0D" blockId="21.[809,1425,598,682]" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFC99FDE3239AFDCF" box="[809,1020,598,620]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Species included:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFBBAFDE223C8FD2E" authority="(Greer et al., 2005)" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" baseAuthorityYear="2005" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Alpinoscincus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alpinus" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFBBAFDE2255FFDC8" bold="true" box="[1034,1337,598,620]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Alpinoscincus alpinus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFD782907C02CA6FFAFBFDE223C3FD2F" author="Greer AE &amp; Allison A &amp; Cogger HG" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" pagination="153 - 179" refId="ref44587" refString="Greer AE, Allison A, Cogger HG. 2005. Four new species of Lobulia (Lacertilia: Scincidae) from high altitude in New Guinea. Herpetological Monographs 19: 153 - 179." type="journal article" year="2005">
Greer 
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFC99FDC22307FD2E" box="[809,865,629,651]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">et al.</emphasis>
, 2005
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFC05FDC1245DFD2E" bold="true" box="[949,1083,629,650]" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2019E087C02CA6FFC05FDC1245DFD2E" box="[949,1083,629,650]" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
; 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFBF9FDC1239BFD0D" authority="(Greer et al., 2005)" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" baseAuthorityYear="2005" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Alpinoscincus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="subalpinus" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFBF9FDC125F7FD2F" bold="true" box="[1097,1425,629,651]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Alpinoscincus subalpinus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFD782907C02CA6FFC81FD202393FD0E" author="Greer AE &amp; Allison A &amp; Cogger HG" box="[817,1013,660,682]" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" pagination="153 - 179" refId="ref44587" refString="Greer AE, Allison A, Cogger HG. 2005. Four new species of Lobulia (Lacertilia: Scincidae) from high altitude in New Guinea. Herpetological Monographs 19: 153 - 179." type="journal article" year="2005">
Greer 
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFCCAFD2023D4FD0D" box="[890,946,660,681]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">et al.</emphasis>
, 2005
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFBB4FD2024EFFD0D" bold="true" box="[1028,1161,660,681]" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2019E087C02CA6FFBB4FD2024EFFD0D" box="[1028,1161,660,681]" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35CACEA7C02CA6FFC99FD66247DFC7A" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BF9FF617C02CA6FFC99FD66247DFC7A" blockId="21.[809,1425,722,990]" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFC99FD6623A3FD43" box="[809,965,722,743]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Distribution:</emphasis>
The two species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFB0AFD662507FD43" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" box="[1210,1377,722,743]" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Alpinoscincus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFB0AFD662507FD43" box="[1210,1377,722,743]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Alpinoscincus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are restricted to extremely high elevations (&gt; 
<quantity id="4CBE52847C02CA6FFAB3FD452530FCA2" box="[1283,1366,753,774]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" unit="m" value="2700.0">2700 m</quantity>
a.s.l. in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFCFAFCA423A0FC81" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[842,966,784,805]" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Alpinoscincus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alpinus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFCFAFCA423A0FC81" box="[842,966,784,805]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">A. alpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and&gt; 
<quantity id="4CBE52847C02CA6FFBADFCA42410FC81" box="[1053,1142,784,806]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" unit="m" value="2350.0">2350 m</quantity>
a.s.l. in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFB52FCA425EEFC81" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[1250,1416,784,805]" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Alpinoscincus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="subalpinus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFB52FCA425EEFC81" box="[1250,1416,784,805]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">A. subalpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) in the north-western Owen Stanley Range in the Papuan Peninsula. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFBA3FCF9257AFCC6" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[1043,1308,845,866]" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Alpinoscincus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alpinus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFBA3FCF9257AFCC6" box="[1043,1308,845,866]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Alpinoscincus alpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in the Murray Range, the Wharton Range, and on Mt Albert Edward and Mt Yule. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFBDCFC3E25F6FC3B" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[1132,1424,906,927]" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Alpinoscincus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="subalpinus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFBDCFC3E25F6FC3B" box="[1132,1424,906,927]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Alpinoscincus subalpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs farther to the north-west, in the vicinity of Wau and Mt Missim.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35CACEA7C02CA6FFC99FBB223F9FB33" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF9FF617C02CA6FFC99FBB223F9FB33" blockId="21.[809,1425,1030,1175]" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">
<emphasis id="B93223737C02CA6FFC99FBB223F1FBBF" box="[809,919,1030,1051]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="241">Remarks:</emphasis>
Molecular evidence suggests that another undescribed species occurs on the summit of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C02CA6FFADFFB9123F5FBFE" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Miscanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="21" pageNumber="241" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="victoria">Mt Victoria</taxonomicName>
, but the specimen (BPBM 47913) was unavailable for morphological examination at the time of writing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
